# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: copyright-infringement
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] After Reddit was sold to Condé Nast Publications in 2006, Swartz became more involved in activism, helping launch the Progressive Change Campaign Committee in 2009.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In 2010, he became a research fellow at Harvard University's Safra Research Lab on Institutional Corruption, directed by Lawrence Lessig.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] He founded the online group Demand Progress, known for its campaign against the Stop Online Piracy Act.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Federal prosecutors, led by Carmen Ortiz, charged him with two counts of wire fraud and eleven violations of the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act, carrying a cumulative maximum penalty of $1 million in fines, 35 years in prison, asset forfeiture, restitution, and supervised release.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz declined a plea bargain under which he would have served six months in federal prison.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Two days after the prosecution rejected a counter-offer by Swartz, he was found dead in his Brooklyn apartment.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In 2013, Swartz was inducted posthumously into the Internet Hall of Fame.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Aaron Hillel Swartz was born in Highland Park, 25 miles (40 kilometers) north of Chicago, to a Jewish family.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] He was the eldest child of Susan and Robert Swartz and brother to Noah and Ben Swartz.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] His father founded the software firm Mark Williams Company.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] At an early age, Swartz immersed himself in the study of computers, programming, the Internet, and Internet culture.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] He attended North Shore Country Day School, a small private school near Chicago, until ninth grade, when he left high school and enrolled in courses at Lake Forest College.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In 1999, at age 12, he created the website The Info Network, a user-generated encyclopedia.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The site won the ArsDigita Prize, given to young people who create "useful, educational, and collaborative" noncommercial websites, and led to early recognition of Swartz's nascent talent in coding.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] At age 14, he became a member of the working group that authored the RSS 1.0 web syndication specification.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] A year later, he became involved in the Creative Commons organization.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In 2004, he enrolled at Stanford University but left the school after his first year.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] During Swartz's first year at Stanford, he applied to Y Combinator's first Summer Founders Program, proposing to work on a startup called Infogami, a flexible content management system designed to create rich and visually interesting websites or a form of wiki for structured data.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] After working on it with co-founder Simon Carstensen over the summer of 2005, Swartz opted not to return to Stanford, choosing instead to continue to develop and seek funding for Infogami.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] As part of his work on Infogami, Swartz created the web.py web application framework because he was unhappy with other available systems in the Python programming language.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In the early fall of 2005, he worked with his fellow co-founders of another nascent Y Combinator firm, Reddit, to rewrite its Lisp codebase using Python and web.py.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Although Infogami's platform was abandoned after Not a Bug was acquired, Infogami's software was used to support the Internet Archive's Open Library project and the web.py web framework was used as the basis for many other projects by Swartz and many others.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] When Infogami failed to find further funding, Y Combinator organizers suggested Infogami merge with Reddit, which it did in November 2005, creating a new firm, Not a Bug, devoted to promoting both products.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] As a result, Swartz was given the title of co-founder of Reddit.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Although both projects initially struggled, Reddit made large gains in popularity in 2005–2006.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In October 2006, based largely on Reddit's success, Not a Bug was acquired by Condé Nast Publications, owner of *Wired* magazine.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz moved with his company to San Francisco to continue to work on Reddit for *Wired*.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] He found corporate office life uncongenial and in January 2007 was asked to resign from the company.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In September 2007, he joined Infogami co-founder Simon Carstensen to launch a new firm, Jottit, in another attempt to create a Markdown-driven content management system in Python.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In 2008, Swartz founded Watchdog.net, "the good government site with teeth", to aggregate and visualize data about politicians.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] That year, he wrote a widely circulated *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto*.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On December 27, 2010, he filed a Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to learn about the treatment of Chelsea Manning, alleged source for WikiLeaks.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] His activism has been praised by digital rights groups such as the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF).
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In 2008, Swartz downloaded about 2.7 million federal court documents stored in the PACER (Public Access to Court Electronic Records) database managed by the Administrative Office of the United States Courts.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The *Huffington Post* characterized his actions this way: "Swartz downloaded public court documents from the PACER system in an effort to make them available outside of the expensive service.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] PACER was charging eight cents per page for information that Carl Malamud, who founded the nonprofit group Public.Resource.Org, contended should be free, because federal documents are not covered by copyright.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The fees were "plowed back to the courts to finance technology, but the system [ran] a budget surplus of some $150 million, according to court reports," reported *The New York Times*.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] After reading Malamud's call for action, Swartz used a Perl computer script running on Amazon cloud servers to download the documents, using credentials belonging to a Sacramento library.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] From September 4 to 20, 2008, it accessed documents and uploaded them to a cloud computing service.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] He released the documents to Malamud's organization.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On September 29, 2008, the GPO suspended the free trial, "pending an evaluation" of the program.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz's actions were subsequently investigated by the FBI.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The case was closed after two months with no charges filed.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] At a 2013 memorial for Swartz, Malamud recalled their work with PACER.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] District Court records out from behind PACER's "pay wall", he said, and found them full of privacy violations, including medical records and the names of minor children and confidential informants.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] A more detailed account of his collaboration with Swartz on the PACER project appears in an essay on Malamud's website.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] *The New York Times* similarly reported Swartz had downloaded "an estimated 20 percent of the entire database".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Based on the facts that Swartz downloaded 2.7 million documents while PACER, at the time, contained 500 million, Lee concluded that Swartz downloaded less than one percent of the database.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In 2009, wanting to learn about effective activism, Swartz helped launch the Progressive Change Campaign Committee.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In 2010, Swartz co-founded Demand Progress, a political advocacy group that organizes people online to "take action by contacting Congress and other leaders, funding pressure tactics, and spreading the word" about civil liberties, government reform, and other issues.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] During academic year 2010–11, Swartz conducted research studies on political corruption as a Lab Fellow in Harvard University's Edmond J.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Safra Research Lab on Institutional Corruption.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Now it's up to you to change the system. ...
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] After the bill's defeat, Swartz was the keynote speaker at the F2C:Freedom to Connect 2012 event in Washington, D.C., on May 21, 2012.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] He added, "We won this fight because everyone made themselves the hero of their own story.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz also spoke on the topic at an event organized by ThoughtWorks.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz participated in Wikipedia beginning in August 2003 under the username AaronSw.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In 2006, he ran unsuccessfully for the Wikimedia Foundation's Board of Trustees.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz came to his conclusions by counting the number of characters editors added to particular articles, while Wales counted the total number of edits.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In January 2013, shortly after he died, WikiLeaks said that Aaron Swartz had helped WikiLeaks and talked to Julian Assange in 2010 and 2011.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] WikiLeaks also said they had "strong reasons to believe, but cannot prove" he may have been a source, possibly breaking WikiLeaks' rules about source anonymity.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] WikiLeaks may have made the statements to imply that Swartz was targeted by the US Attorney's Office and Secret Service in order to get at WikiLeaks.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] According to state and federal authorities, Swartz used JSTOR, a digital repository, to download a large number of academic journal articles through MIT's computer network over the course of a few weeks in late 2010 and early 2011.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Visitors to MIT's "open campus" were authorized to access JSTOR through its network; Swartz, as a research fellow at Harvard University, also had a JSTOR account.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On September 25, 2010, the IP address 18.55.6.215, part of the MIT network, began sending hundreds of PDF download requests per minute to the JSTOR website, enough to slow the site's performance.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] This prompted a block of the IP address.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In the morning, another IP address, also from within the MIT network, began sending more PDF download requests, resulting in a temporary block on the firewall level of all MIT computers in the entire 18.0.0.0/8 range.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] According to authorities, Swartz downloaded the documents through a laptop connected to a networking switch in a controlled-access wiring closet at MIT.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The closet's door was kept unlocked, according to press reports.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] When it was discovered, a video camera was placed in the room to record Swartz; his computer was left untouched.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The recording was stopped once Swartz was identified, but rather than pursue a civil lawsuit against him, JSTOR settled with him in June 2011; under the terms of the settlement, he surrendered the downloaded data.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On July 30, 2013, JSTOR released 300 partially redacted documents used as incriminating evidence against Swartz, originally sent to the United States Attorney's Office in response to subpoenas in the case *United States v.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On the night of January 6, 2011, Swartz was arrested near the Harvard campus by MIT Police and a Secret Service agent, and arraigned in Cambridge District Court on two state charges of breaking and entering with intent to commit a felony.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On July 11, 2011, he was indicted by a federal grand jury on charges of wire fraud, computer fraud, unlawfully obtaining information from a protected computer, and recklessly damaging a protected computer.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On November 17, 2011, Swartz was indicted by a Middlesex County Superior Court grand jury on state charges of breaking and entering with intent, grand larceny, and unauthorized access to a computer network.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On December 16, 2011, state prosecutors filed a notice that they were dropping the two original charges, and the charges listed in the November 17, 2011, indictment were dropped on March 8, 2012.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] According to a spokesperson for the Middlesex County prosecutor, this was done to avoid impeding a federal prosecution headed by Stephen P.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Heymann, supported by evidence provided by Secret Service agent Michael S.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On September 12, 2012, federal prosecutors filed a superseding indictment adding nine more felony counts, increasing Swartz's maximum criminal exposure to 50 years of imprisonment and $1 million in fines.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] During plea negotiations with Swartz's attorneys, the prosecutors offered to recommend a sentence of six months in a low-security prison if Swartz pled guilty to 13 federal crimes.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz and his lead attorney rejected the deal, opting instead for a trial where prosecutors would be forced to justify their pursuit of him.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The federal prosecution involved what was characterized by numerous critics (such as former Nixon White House counsel John Dean) as an "overcharging" 13-count indictment and "overzealous", "Nixonian" prosecution for alleged computer crimes, brought by then U.S.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Attorney for Massachusetts Carmen Ortiz.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz died by suicide on January 11, 2013.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] After his death, federal prosecutors dropped the charges.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On December 4, 2013, due to a Freedom of Information Act suit by the investigations editor of *Wired* magazine, several documents related to the case were released by the Secret Service, including a video of Swartz entering the MIT network closet.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz was in an open relationship with Quinn Norton between 2007 and 2011 and dated Taren Stinebrickner-Kauffman from 2011 until his death in 2013, contemplating marriage with her.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] He also reportedly had same-sex relationships, and was skeptical of the idea of sexual identity.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Aside from his work, he posted frequently on Twitter, Reddit and his personal website.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On the evening of January 11, 2013, Swartz's girlfriend, Stinebrickner-Kauffman, found him dead in his Brooklyn apartment.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] A spokesperson for New York's Medical Examiner reported that he had hanged himself.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Days before Swartz's funeral, Lawrence Lessig eulogized him in an essay, "Prosecutor as Bully".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] He decried the disproportionality of Swartz's prosecution and said, "The question this government needs to answer is why it was so necessary that Aaron Swartz be labeled a 'felon'.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] For in the 18 months of negotiations, that was what he was not willing to accept." Cory Doctorow wrote, "Aaron had an unbeatable combination of political insight, technical skill, and intelligence about people and issues.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] I think he could have revolutionized American (and worldwide) politics.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz's funeral services were held on January 15, 2013, at Central Avenue Synagogue in Highland Park, Illinois.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Tim Berners-Lee, creator of the World Wide Web, delivered a eulogy.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] He is buried at Shalom Memorial Park in Arlington Heights.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The same day, *The Wall Street Journal* published a story based in part on an interview with Taren Stinebrickner-Kauffman.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] She told the *Journal* that Swartz lacked the money to pay for a trial and "it was too hard for him to ... make that part of his life go public" by asking for help.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] He was also distressed, she said, because two of his friends had just been subpoenaed and because he no longer believed that MIT would try to stop the prosecution.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] For donations in his memory, Swartz's family recommended GiveWell, an organization Swartz admired, had collaborated with, and made his sole beneficiary in his will.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On January 19, hundreds attended a memorial at the Cooper Union, speakers at which included Taren Stinebrickner-Kauffman, open source advocate Doc Searls, Creative Commons' Glenn Otis Brown, journalist Quinn Norton, Roy Singham of ThoughtWorks, and David Segal of Demand Progress.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On January 24, there was a memorial at the Internet Archive headquarters in San Francisco (video) at which Stinebrickner-Kauffman, Alex Stamos, Brewster Kahle, Peter Eckersley, and Carl Malamud spoke.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On February 4, a memorial was held in the Cannon House Office Building on Capitol Hill; speakers included Senator Ron Wyden and Representatives Darrell Issa, Alan Grayson, and Jared Polis.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Other lawmakers in attendance included Senator Elizabeth Warren and Representatives Zoe Lofgren and Jan Schakowsky.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Harvey Silverglate was a featured speaker at a Demand Progress rally in Swartz's memory.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] A memorial also took place on March 12 at the MIT Media Lab.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On February 2, 2025, a statue of Swartz was unveiled at the Internet Archive building in San Francisco.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] This was organized by Pablo Peniche and Lisa Rein.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The statue stands in the building's lobby.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Attorney for the District of Massachusetts, said in a statement: "As a parent and a sister, I can only imagine the pain felt by the family and friends of Aaron Swartz, ...
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On January 12, 2013, Swartz's family and partner issued a statement criticizing the prosecutors and MIT.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] At the time, MIT maintained an open-campus policy along with an "open network".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Two days after Swartz's death, MIT President L.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Rafael Reif commissioned professor Hal Abelson to lead an analysis of MIT's options and decisions relating to Swartz's "legal struggles".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] To help guide the fact-finding stage of the review, MIT created a website where community members could suggest questions and issues for the review to address.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz's attorneys requested that all pretrial discovery documents be made public, a move MIT opposed.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz allies have criticized MIT's opposition to releasing the evidence.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On July 26, 2013, the Abelson panel submitted a report to Reif, who authorized its public release on July 30.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The panel reported that MIT had not supported charges against Swartz and cleared the institution of wrongdoing, but also noted that despite MIT's advocacy for open access culture at the institutional level and beyond, the university never extended that support to Swartz.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The report revealed, for example, that while MIT considered issuing a public statement about its position on the case, it never did so.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] As editor Hrag Vartanian writes in *Hyperallergic*, the Brooklyn muralist BAMN ("By Any Means Necessary") created a mural of Swartz.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] "Swartz was an amazing human being who fought tirelessly for our right to a free and open Internet", BAMN said.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] "He was much more than just the 'Reddit guy'." On April 17, 2013, Yuval Noah Harari called Swartz "the first martyr of the Freedom of Information movement".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] But according to Harari, Swartz's stance did not illustrate belief in the freedom of persons or speech but stemmed from his generation's conviction that above all else, information should be free.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz's legacy has reportedly strengthened the open access to scholarship movement.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In Illinois, his home state, Swartz's influence led state university faculties to adopt policies in favor of open access.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On January 13, 2013, members of Anonymous hacked two websites on the MIT domain, replacing them with tributes to Swartz that called on members of the Internet community to use his death as a rallying point for the open access movement.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The banner included a list of demands for improvements in the U.S. copyright system, along with Swartz's *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto.* On the night of January 18, MIT's email system was taken offline for ten hours.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On January 22, email sent to MIT was redirected by hackers Aush0k and TibitXimer to the Korea Advanced Institute of Science & Technology.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] All other traffic to MIT was redirected to a computer at Harvard University that was publishing a statement headed "R.I.P Aaron Swartz", with text from a 2009 post by Swartz, accompanied by a chiptune version of "The Star-Spangled Banner".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] MIT regained full control after about seven hours.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In the early hours of January 26, Anonymous hacked the U.S.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Sentencing Commission website, USSC.gov.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The homepage was replaced by an embedded YouTube video, *Anonymous Operation Last Resort*.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The video statement said Swartz "faced an impossible choice".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] A hacker downloaded "hundreds of thousands" of scientific-journal articles from a Swiss publisher's website and republished them on the open Web in Swartz's honor a week before the first anniversary of his death.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] After Swartz's death, more than 50,000 people signed an online petition to the White House calling for Ortiz's removal "for overreach in the case of Aaron Swartz".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] A similar petition was submitted calling for prosecutor Stephen Heymann's firing.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In January 2015, the White House declined both petitions.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On August 3, 2013, Swartz was posthumously inducted into the Internet Hall of Fame.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] A hackathon was held in Swartz's memory around the date of his birthday in 2013.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On the weekend of November 8–10, 2013, inspired by Swartz's work and life, a second annual hackathon was held in at least 16 cities around the world.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Preliminary topics worked on at the 2013 Aaron Swartz Hackathon were privacy and software tools, transparency, activism, access, legal fixes, and a low-cost book scanner.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In January 2014, Lawrence Lessig led a walk across New Hampshire in honor of Swartz, rallying for campaign finance reform.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In 2017, the Turkish-Dutch artist Ahmet Öğüt commemorated Swartz in a work titled "Information Power to The People", which depicted his bust.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz's supporters responded to news of his death with an effort called #PDFTribute to promote Open Access.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On January 12, Eva Vivalt, a development economist at the World Bank, began posting her academic articles online using the hashtag *#pdftribute* as a tribute to Swartz.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz's story has exposed the topic of open access to scientific publications to wider audiences.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Many institutions and personalities have since campaigned for open access to scientific knowledge.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz's death prompted calls for more open access to scholarly data (e.g., open science data).
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The Think Computer Foundation and the Center for Information Technology Policy (CITP) at Princeton University announced scholarships awarded in memory of Swartz.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In 2013, Swartz was posthumously awarded the American Library Association's James Madison Award for being an "outspoken advocate for public participation in government and unrestricted access to peer-reviewed scholarly articles".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In March, the editor and editorial board of the *Journal of Library Administration* resigned *en masse*, citing a dispute with the journal's publisher, Routledge.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] One board member wrote of a "crisis of conscience about publishing in a journal that was not open access" after Swartz died.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In 2002, Swartz had said that when he died, he wanted the contents of his hard drives made publicly available.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] House of Representatives—Republican Darrell Issa and Democrats Zoe Lofgren and Jared Polis—all on the House Judiciary Committee, raised questions about the government's handling of the case.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Calling the charges against him "ridiculous and trumped up", Polis called Swartz a "martyr" whose death illustrated the need for Congress to limit the discretion of federal prosecutors.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Senator Elizabeth Warren issued a statement saying that Swartz's "advocacy for Internet freedom, social justice, and Wall Street reform demonstrated ... the power of his ideas".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In a letter to Attorney General Eric Holder, Senator John Cornyn asked, "On what basis did the U.S.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Attorney for the District of Massachusetts conclude that her office's conduct was 'appropriate'?" and "Was the prosecution of Mr.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Issa, who chaired the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform, announced that he would investigate the Justice Department's actions in prosecuting Swartz.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In a statement to *The Huffington Post*, he praised Swartz's work on "open government and free access to the people".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Issa's investigation garnered some bipartisan support.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On January 28, 2013, Issa and ranking committee member Elijah Cummings published a letter to Holder asking why federal prosecutors had filed the superseding indictment.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On February 20, WBUR reported that Ortiz was expected to testify at an upcoming Oversight Committee hearing about her office's handling of Swartz's case.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On February 22, Associate Deputy Attorney General Steven Reich conducted a briefing for congressional staffers involved in the investigation.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] They were told that Swartz's *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto* played a role in prosecutorial decision-making.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Congressional staffers left this briefing believing that prosecutors thought Swartz had to be convicted of a felony carrying at least a short prison sentence in order to justify having filed charges against him.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Excoriating the Department of Justice as the "Department of Vengeance", Stinebrickner-Kauffman told the *Guardian* that the DOJ had erred in relying on Swartz's *Guerilla Open Access Manifesto* as an indication of his beliefs by 2010.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] She said, "He was no longer a single issue activist.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] He was into lots of things, from healthcare to climate change to money in politics." On March 6, Holder testified before the Senate Judiciary Committee that the case was "a good use of prosecutorial discretion".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In response, Stinebrickner-Kauffman issued a statement repeating and amplifying her claims of prosecutorial misconduct.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On March 22, Senator Al Franken wrote in a letter to Holder that "charging a young man like Mr.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In 2013, Lofgren introduced a bill, *Aaron's Law* (H.R.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] 1196), to exclude terms of service violations from the 1986 Computer Fraud and Abuse Act and from the wire fraud statute.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Lessig wrote of the bill, "this is a critically important change....
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The CFAA was the hook for the government's bullying....
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In a single line: no longer would it be a felony to breach a contract." Professor Orin Kerr, a specialist in the nexus between computer law and criminal law, wrote that he had been arguing for precisely this sort of reform of the Act for years.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The ACLU also called for reform of the CFAA to "remove the dangerously broad criminalization of online activity".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The EFF mounted a campaign for these reforms.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Lessig's inaugural Chair lecture as Furman Professor of Law and Leadership was titled *Aaron's Laws: Law and Justice in a Digital Age*; he dedicated the lecture to Swartz.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The Aaron's Law bill stalled in committee.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Brian Knappenberger alleges this was due to Oracle Corporation's financial interest in maintaining the status quo.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The Fair Access to Science and Technology Research Act (FASTR) is a bill that would mandate earlier public release of taxpayer-funded research.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] FASTR has been described as "The Other Aaron's Law".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Senators Wyden and Cornyn introduced the Senate version in 2013, 2015 and 2017, while the bill was introduced to the House of Representatives by Lofgren, Mike Doyle, and Kevin Yoder.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Wyden wrote of the bill, "the FASTR act provides that access to taxpayer funded research should never be hidden behind a paywall." The legislation did not pass, but it prompted more open access on the part of the US government.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Since 2013, Aaron Swartz Day has been celebrated on his birthday, November 8, with hackathons and livestreamed talks related to the many issues Swartz was passionate about, such as open access and progressive politics and economics.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Past speakers include Chelsea Manning, Barrett Brown, Trevor Timm of the Freedom of the Press Foundation, Cory Doctorow, Cindy Cohn, Jason Leopold, and Brewster Kahle.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz has been featured in various works of art and has posthumously received dedications from numerous artists.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] He appeared in a few documentaries, including *Aardvark'd: 12 Weeks with Geeks* in 2005.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] After leaving Reddit he appeared in *Steal This Film II* (2007).
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Swartz's first posthumous work was in 2013, when Kenneth Goldsmith dedicated his "Printing out the Internet" exhibition to Swartz.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] On January 11, 2014, marking the first anniversary of his death, a preview was released of *The Internet's Own Boy: The Story of Aaron Swartz*, a documentary about Swartz, the NSA and SOPA.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The film was officially released at the January 2014 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] *Democracy Now!* covered the release of the documentary, as well as Swartz's life and legal case, in a sprawling interview with director Brian Knappenberger, Swartz's father, brother, and his attorney.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The documentary is released under a Creative Commons License; it debuted in theaters and on-demand in June 2014.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Mashable called the documentary "a powerful homage to Aaron Swartz".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Its debut at Sundance received a standing ovation.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In October 2014, *Killswitch*, a documentary film featuring Swartz, Lessig, Tim Wu, and Edward Snowden, premiered at the Woodstock Film Festival, where it won the award for Best Editing.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The film focuses on Swartz's role in advocating for internet freedoms.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] In February 2015, Congressman Alan Grayson invited *Killswitch* to screen at the Capitol Visitor Center in Washington, D.C.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The event was held on the eve of the Federal Communications Commission's historic decision on net neutrality.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] At the event, Grayson, Lessig, and Free Press CEO Craig Aaron spoke about Swartz and his fight for a free and open Internet.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Grayson called *Killswitch* "one of the most honest accounts of the battle to control the Internet—and access to information itself." Richard von Busack of the Metro Silicon Valley said *Killswitch* contains "some of the most lapidary use of found footage this side of The Atomic Café".
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Fred Swegles of the *Orange County Register* wrote, "Anyone who values unfettered access to online information is apt to be captivated by *Killswitch*, a gripping and fast-paced documentary." Kathy Gill of GeekWire wrote, "*Killswitch* is much more than a dry recitation of technical history.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Director Ali Akbarzadeh, producer Jeff Horn, and writer Chris Dollar created a human-centered story.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] He appeared in the unreleased film *War for the Web* where he had been interviewed a year prior to his death.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] The documentary was ultimately cancelled as it failed to reach its funding goal, but the footage was later used in *The Internet's Own Boy*.
[src:copyright-infringement/aaron-swartz] Another biographical film about Swartz, *Think Aaron*, was being developed by HBO Films as of 2020.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] If a software product reaches end-of-life and becomes abandonware, users are confronted with several potential problems: missing purchase availability (besides used software) and missing technical support, e.g. compatibility fixes for newer hardware and operating systems.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] These problems are exacerbated if software is bound to physical media with a limited life-expectancy (floppy disks, optical media etc.) and backups are impossible because of copy protection or copyright law.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] If a software is distributed only in a digital, DRM-locked form or as SaaS, the shutdown of the servers will lead to a public loss of the software.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] If the software product is without alternatives, the missing replacement availability becomes a challenge for continued software usage.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Once a software product becomes abandonware, there is a high risk that the source code becomes lost or irrecoverable even for its original developers, as multiple cases have shown.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] One of many examples is the closure of Atari in Sunnyvale, California in 1996, when the original source codes of several milestones of video game history (such as *Asteroids* and *Centipede*) were thrown out as trash, some of which were later recovered.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] After the closure of Tapulous, Tap Tap Revenge became abandonware.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] There is also no way to retrieve the source code due to the app being sandboxed, thus making preserving it borderline impossible.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Unavailability of software and the associated source code can also be a hindrance for software archaeology and research.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] As response to the missing availability of abandonware, people have distributed old software since shortly after the beginning of personal computing, but the activity remained low-key until the advent of the Internet.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] While trading old games has taken many names and forms, the term "abandonware" was coined by Peter Ringering in late 1996.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Ringering found classic game websites similar to his own, contacted their webmasters, and formed the original *Abandonware Ring* in February 1997.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] This original webring was little more than a collection of sites linking to adventureclassicgaming.com.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Another was a site indexing them all to provide a rudimentary search facility.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] In October 1997, the Interactive Digital Software Association sent cease and desist letters to all sites within the Abandonware Ring, which led to most shutting down.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] An unintended consequence was that it spurred others to create new abandonware sites and organizations that came to outnumber the original Ring members.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Sites formed after the demise of the original Abandonware Ring include Abandonia, Bunny Abandonware and Home of the Underdogs.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] In later years abandonware websites actively acquired and received permissions from developers and copyright holders (e.g.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Jeff Minter, Magnetic Fields or Gremlin Interactive) for legal redistribution of abandoned works; an example is *World of Spectrum* who acquired the permission from many developers and successfully retracted a DMCA case.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Several websites archive abandonware for download, including old versions of applications that are difficult to find by any other means.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] The Internet Archive has created an archive of what it describes as "vintage software", as a way to preserve them.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] The project advocated for an exemption from the United States Digital Millennium Copyright Act to permit them to bypass copy protection, which was approved in 2003 for a period of three years.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] The exemption was renewed in 2006, and as of 27 October 2009, has been indefinitely extended pending further rulemakings.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Since 23 December 2014 the Internet Archive presents via a browser based DOSBox emulation thousands of archived DOS/PC games for "*scholarship and research purposes only*".
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Starting around 2006, the Library of Congress began the long-time preservation of video games with the *game canon* list.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] In September 2012 the collection had nearly 3,000 games from many platforms and also around 1,500 strategy guides.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] For instance, the source code of the unreleased PlayStation Portable game *Duke Nukem: Critical Mass* was discovered in August 2014 to be preserved at the Library of Congress.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Since around 2009 the International Center for the History of Electronic Games (ICHEG) has taken a five-pronged approach to video game preservation: original software and hardware, marketing materials and publications, production records, play capture, and finally the source code.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] In December 2013 the ICHEG received a donation of several SSI video games, for instance Computer Bismarck, including the source code for preservation.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] In 2014 a collection of Broderbund games and a "virtually complete" Atari arcade machine source code and asset collection was added.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] In response to the missing software support, sometimes the software's user community begins to provide support (bug fixes, compatibility adaptions etc.) even without available source code, internal software documentation and original developer tools.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Methods are debugging, reverse engineering of file and data formats, and hacking the binary executables.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Often the results are distributed as unofficial patches.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Notable examples are *Fallout 2*, *Vampire: The Masquerade – Bloodlines* or even Windows 98.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] With the new possibility of digital distribution arising in mid-2000, the commercial distribution for many old titles became feasible again as deployment and storage costs dropped significantly.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] A digital distributor specialized in bringing old games out of abandonware is *GOG.com* (formerly called *Good Old Games*) who started in 2008 to search for copyright holders of classic games to release them legally and DRM-free again.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] For instance, on December 9, 2013, the real-time strategy video game *Conquest: Frontier Wars* was, after ten years of non-availability, re-released by gog.com, also including the source code.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Proponents of abandonware preservation argue that it is more ethical to make copies of such software than new software that still sells.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Some have incorrectly taken this to mean that abandonware is legal to distribute, although no software written since 1964 is old enough for copyright to have expired in the US.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Even in cases where the original company no longer exists, the rights usually belong to someone else, though no one may be able to trace actual ownership, including the owners themselves.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Abandonware advocates also frequently cite historical preservation as a reason for trading abandoned software.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Older computer media are fragile and prone to rapid deterioration, necessitating transfer of these materials to more modern, stable media and generation of many copies to ensure the software will not simply disappear.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Users of still-functional older computer systems argue for the need of abandonware because re-release of software by copyright holders will most likely target modern systems or incompatible media instead, preventing legal purchase of compatible software.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Some game developers showed sympathy for abandonware websites as they preserve their classical game titles.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] In most cases, software classed as abandonware is not in the public domain, as it has never had its original copyright officially revoked and some company or individual may still own rights.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] By default, this may allow the product to *de facto* lapse into the public domain to such an extent that enforcement becomes impractical.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Rarely has any abandonware case gone to court, but it is still unlawful to distribute copies of old copyrighted software and games, with or without compensation, in any Berne Convention signatory country.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Old copyrights are usually left undefended.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] This can be due to intentional non-enforcement by owners due to software age or obsolescence, but sometimes results from a corporate copyright holder going out of business without explicitly transferring ownership, leaving no one aware of the right to defend the copyright.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Even if the copyright is not defended, copying of such software is still unlawful in most jurisdictions when a copyright is still in effect.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Abandonware changes hands on the assumption that the resources required to enforce copyrights outweigh benefits a copyright holder might realize from selling software licenses.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Additionally, abandonware proponents argue that distributing software for which there is no one to defend the copyright is morally acceptable, even where unsupported by current law.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Companies that have gone out of business without transferring their copyrights are an example of this; many hardware and software companies that developed older systems are long since out of business and precise documentation of the copyrights may not be readily available.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Often the availability of abandonware on the Internet is related to the willingness of copyright holders to defend their copyrights.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] For example, unencumbered games for Colecovision are markedly easier to find on the Internet than unencumbered games for Mattel Intellivision in large part because there is still a company that sells Intellivision games while no such company exists for the Colecovision.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] The Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA) can be a problem for the preservation of old software as it prohibits required techniques.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] In October 2003, the US Congress passed 4 clauses to the DMCA which allow for reverse engineering software in case of preservation.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] In November 2006 the Library of Congress approved an exemption to the DMCA that permits the cracking of copy protection on software no longer being sold or supported by its copyright holder so that they can be archived and preserved without fear of retribution.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Currently, US copyright law does not recognize the term or concept of "abandonware" while the general concept "orphan works" is recognized (see Orphan works in the United States).
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] There is a long-held concept of abandonment in trademark law as a direct result of the infinite term of trademark protection.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Currently, a copyright can be released into the public domain if the owner clearly does so in writing; however this formal process is not considered abandoning, but rather releasing.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Those who do not own a copyright cannot merely claim the copyright abandoned and start using protected works without permission of the copyright holder, who could then seek legal remedy.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Hosting and distributing copyrighted software without permission is illegal.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Copyright holders, sometimes through the Entertainment Software Association, send cease and desist letters, and some sites have shut down or removed infringing software as a result.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] However, most of the Association's efforts are devoted to new games, due to those titles possessing the greatest value.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] In the EU in 2012, an "Orphan Works Directive" (Directive 2012/28/EU) was constituted and is transferred into the members' laws.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] While the terminology has ambiguities regarding software and especially video games, some scholars argue that abandonware software video games fall under the definition of *audiovisual works* mentioned there.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Once the copyright on a piece of software has expired, it automatically falls into public domain.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Such software can be legally distributed without restrictions.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] However, due to the length of copyright terms in most countries, this has yet to happen for most software.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] All countries that observe the Berne Convention enforce copyright ownership for at least 50 years after publication or the author's death.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] However, individual countries may choose to enforce copyrights for longer periods.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] In the United States, copyright durations are determined based on authorship.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] For most published works, the duration is 70 years after the author's death.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] However, for anonymous works, works published under a pseudonym or works made for hire, the duration is 120 years after creation, or 95 years after publication, whichever comes first.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] In France, copyright durations are 70 years after the relevant date (date of author's death or publication) for either class.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] However, because of the length of copyright enforcement in most countries, it is likely that by the time a piece of software defaults to public domain, it will have long become obsolete, irrelevant, or incompatible with any existing hardware.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Additionally, due to the relatively short commercial, as well as physical, lifespans of most digital media, it is entirely possible that by the time the copyright expires for a piece of software, it will no longer exist in any form.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] However, since the largest risk in dealing with abandonware is that of distribution, this may be mitigated somewhat by private users (or organizations such as the Internet Archive) making private copies of such software, which would then be legally redistributable at the time of copyright expiry.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] There are alternatives for companies with a software product which faces the end-of-life instead of abandoning the software in an unsupported state.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Some user-communities convince companies to voluntarily relinquish copyright on software, putting it into the public domain, or re-license it as freeware.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Unlike so-called *abandonware*, it is perfectly legal to transfer public domain or freely licensed software.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Amstrad is an example which supports emulation and free distribution of CPC and ZX Spectrum hardware ROMs and software.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Borland released "antique software" as freeware.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Smith Engineering permits not-for-profit reproduction and distribution of Vectrex games and documentation.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Groups that lobby companies to release their software as freeware have met with mixed results.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] One example is the library of educational titles released by MECC.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] MECC was sold to Broderbund, which was sold to The Learning Company.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] When TLC was contacted about releasing classic MECC titles as freeware, the documentation proving that TLC held the rights to these titles could not be located, and therefore the rights for these titles are "in limbo" and may never be legally released.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Lost or unclear copyrights to vintage out-of-print software is not uncommon, as rights to the *No One Lives Forever* series illustrates.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] The problem of missing technical support for a software can be most effectively solved when the source code becomes available.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Therefore, several companies decided to release the source code specifically to allow the user communities to provide further technical software support (bug fixes, compatibility adaptions etc.) themselves, e.g. by community patches or source ports to new computing platforms.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] For instance, in December 2015 Microsoft released the Windows Live Writer source code to allow the community to continue the support.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Id Software and 3D Realms are early proponents in this practice, releasing the source code for the game engines of some older titles under a free software license (but not the actual game content, such as levels or textures).
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] — Kevin Klemmick, interviewed by *Bertolone, Giorgio (March 12, 2011).
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] "Interview with Kevin Klemmick - Lead Software Engineer for Falcon 4.0".
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Archived from the original on March 18, 2011.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] The chilling effect of drawing a possible lawsuit can discourage release of source code.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Efforts to persuade IBM to release OS/2 as open source software were ignored since some of the code was co-developed by Microsoft.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Nevertheless, several notable examples of successfully opened commercial software exist, for instance, the web browser Netscape Communicator, which was released by Netscape Communications on March 31, 1998.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] The development was continued under the umbrella of the Mozilla Foundation and Netscape Communicator became the basis of several browsers, such as Mozilla Firefox.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] There are also many examples in the video game domain: Revolution Software released their game *Beneath a Steel Sky* as freeware and gave the engine's source code to the authors of ScummVM to add support for the game.
[src:copyright-infringement/abandonware] Other examples are *Myth II*, *Call to Power II* and Microsoft's *Allegiance* which were released to allow the community to continue the support.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The **Abstraction-Filtration-Comparison test** (AFC) is a method of identifying substantial similarity for the purposes of applying copyright law.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] In particular, the AFC test is used to determine whether non-literal elements of a computer program have been copied by comparing the protectable elements of two programs.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The AFC test was developed by the United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit in 1992 in its opinion for *Computer Associates Int.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] Altai Inc.* It has been widely adopted by United States courts and recognized by courts outside the United States as well.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The Second Circuit Court of Appeals developed the AFC test for use in *Computer Associates Int'l, Inc. v.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] Altai Inc.* In that case, Computer Associates sued Altai for copyright infringement of a computer job scheduler program that was designed to be easily ported between operating systems.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] Proving copyright infringement requires proving both ownership of the copyright and that copying took place.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] This second requirement can be met either by direct proof, or as is more usually done, by demonstrating the following: 1) the defendant had access to the copyright material and 2) there is substantial similarity between the copyrighted work and the defendant's work.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] Demonstrating substantial similarity can be difficult when the two works are not exact replicas, either in full or in part.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The Second Circuit court had found there was little previous guidance on how best to do this.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] One notable previous treatment of substantial similarity of the structure, sequence and organization (SSO) of software was adopted by the Third Circuit in *Whelan v.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The court there suggested identifying the main function of a program as the idea and everything that is not strictly necessary for the purposes of the idea can be considered expression.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The *Altai* court declined to follow this method, noting that the *Whelan* method "did not place enough emphasis on practical considerations".
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The AFC test was devised to handle that issue; it is a method for determining whether substantial similarity exists between two computer programs, especially in non-literal elements of the program.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The AFC test is a three-step process for determining substantial similarity of the non-literal elements of a computer program.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The process requires the court to first identify the increasing levels of abstraction of the program.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] Then, at each level of abstraction, material that is not protectable by copyright is identified and filtered out from further examination.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The final step is to compare the defendant's program to the plaintiff's, looking only at the copyright-protected material as identified in the previous two steps, and determine whether the plaintiff's work was copied.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] In addition, the court will assess the relative significance of any copied material with respect to the entire program.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The purpose of the abstraction step is to identify which aspects of the program constitute its expression and which are the ideas.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] By what is commonly referred to as the idea/expression dichotomy, copyright law protects an author's expression, but not the idea behind that expression.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] In a computer program, the lowest level of abstraction, the concrete code of the program, is clearly expression, while the highest level of abstraction, the general function of the program, might be better classified as the idea behind the program.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The abstractions test was first developed by the Second Circuit for use in literary works, but in the AFC test, they outline how it might be applied to computer programs.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The court identifies possible levels of abstraction that can be defined.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] In increasing order of abstraction; these are: individual instructions, groups of instructions organized into a "hierarchy of modules", the functions of the lowest-level modules, the functions of the higher-level modules, the "ultimate function" of the code.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The second step is to remove from consideration aspects of the program which are not legally protectable by copyright.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The analysis is done at each level of abstraction identified in the previous step.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The court identifies three factors to consider during this step: elements dictated by efficiency, elements dictated by external factors, and elements taken from the public domain.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The court explains that elements dictated by efficiency are removed from consideration based on the merger doctrine which states that a form of expression that is incidental to the idea cannot be protected by copyright.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] In computer programs, concerns for efficiency may limit the possible ways to achieve a particular function, making a particular expression necessary to achieving the idea.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] In this case, the expression is not protected by copyright.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] Eliminating elements dictated by external factors is an application of the scènes à faire doctrine to computer programs.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The doctrine holds that elements necessary for, or standard to, expression in some particular theme cannot be protected by copyright.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] Elements dictated by external factors may include hardware specifications, interoperability and compatibility requirements, design standards, demands of the market being served, and standard programming techniques.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] Finally, material that exists in the public domain can not be copyrighted and is also removed from the analysis.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The final step of the AFC test is to consider the elements of the program identified in the first step and remaining after the second step, and for each of these compare the defendant's work with the plaintiff's to determine if the one is a copy of the other.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] In addition, the court will look at the importance of the copied portion with respect to the entire program.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] Following the *Altai* case, the AFC method has been widely adopted.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] Since 1992, every court to deal with the issue of determining substantial similarity in the non-literal aspects of computer programs has chosen the AFC method over the *Whelan* method.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] Extension of AFC to other (non-computer program) areas of copyright law has been slow, however.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] The analysis of the filtration step has been endorsed by courts in Canada and France.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] In the UK, the AFC test has the dubious honor of being endorsed and disapproved in successive cases.
[src:copyright-infringement/abstraction-filtration-comparison-test] Current English law does not follow the AFC test laid out in Altai.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] The **Access to Knowledge** (**A2K**) **movement** is a loose collection of civil society groups, governments, and individuals converging on the idea that access to knowledge should be linked to fundamental principles of justice, freedom, and economic development.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] A2K emerged in the early 2000s as a global response to growing concerns that restrictive intellectual property laws and digital monopolies were limiting public access to information, education, and cultural resources.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] The movement emphasizes that knowledge is a shared social good that should be available to all people, regardless of geography or economic status.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] The Berlin Declaration on Open Access to Knowledge in the Sciences and Humanities from 2003 is a major declaration reflecting the goals of the movement pertaining to academic publishing.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] In October 2004, the Geneva Declaration on the Future of the World Intellectual Property Organization emerged from a call from Brazil and Argentina for a development agenda for the World Intellectual Property Organization and was supported by hundreds of organizations.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] One of the proposals of the declaration was to a "call for a Treaty on Access to Knowledge and Technology.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] The Standing Committee on Patents and the Standing Committee on Copyright and Related Rights should solicit views from member countries and the public on elements of such a treaty".
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] A shared discussion platform on A2K issues is the mailing list of that name, which was initiated around discussion of the Geneva declaration.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] A draft "A2K treaty" was later produced.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] The proposed treaty is intended to ease the transfer of knowledge to developing nations, and to secure the viability of open innovation systems all over the world.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] The draft A2K Treaty was intended partly to alleviate knowledge gap issues in the Global South, promote the transfer of knowledge and technology, and support open models of innovation.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] The process of drafting the treaty involved workshops and consultations, including a May 2005 "Consultation on Proposed Treaty" meeting in London organized by consumer, library, and knowledge-rights group.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] While the treaty was never formally adopted, it has served as a focal point for coalition-building and strategic framing within the A2K movement.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] Through the 2010s and into the present, the A2K movement's history has become intertwined with, though not identical to, related efforts in open access, open data, digital rights, open educational resources, and free culture.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] Access to knowledge and science is protected by Article 27 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] A2K academics argue that "material interests" are not simply equivalent to current intellectual property provisions, not least because these rights are saleable and transferable, and therefore not "inalienable".
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] The right to access is ultimately the more important part of the right.
[src:copyright-infringement/access-to-knowledge-movement] Many different groups refer to the A2K movement.
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] Since 2008 copyright in Afghanistan has been governed by the law on the support the right of authors, composers, artists and researchers (Copy Right Law).
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] In 1958, Afghanistan ratified the Agreement on the Importation of Educational, Scientific and Cultural Materials, with Annexes A to E and Protocol annexed (Florence, 17 June 1950).
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] It acceded to the WIPO treaty on 13 September 2005, which came into action at the end of the year.
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] In November 2003, the *Copyright World* journal reported that a group, Intellectual Property Working Group of the Afghanistan Transitional Commercial Law Project, had been working on setting up the first patent or copyright system for the country, and updating its trademark laws.
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] It is a joint project of Center for International Management Education (CIME) and the American Bar Association's "Asia Law Initiative" (ABA-Asia).
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] Since 2 June 2018 the Berne Convention is in effect in Afghanistan.
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] As of 2005, Afghanistan has no official copyright relations with the United States, resulting in works published in Afghanistan not being copyrighted in the United States, and vice versa.
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] In October 2007, the US Department of Commerce and the Afghanistan Ministry of Commerce and Industry signed a joint agreement to establish a forum for commercial cooperation including establishing intellectual property rights protection and enforcement.
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] Since joining the WTO in 2016, Afghanistan works are automatically restored in the U.S.
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] To determine which are eligible, an individual must look to Afghanistan law at the time that they joined the WTO or Berne, whichever is older.
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] Only works still under copyright are eligible.
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] For Afghanistan, the term of copyright is life plus 50 for individual and joint works, and for paintings, photographs, and audiovisual works the term is 50 years from first publication.
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] That means that works whose authors died before 1972 are not restored in the U.S., and paintings, photographs, and audiovisual works published before 1972 are not restored.
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] For works published before 1978: the term is 95 years from publication.
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] For all other works (published on or after Jan 1, 1978 and unpublished works), the term is life of the author plus seventy years, or 95/120 for anonymous and work for hire.
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] It was later pointed out that RTA had no right to make such an autonomous declaration.
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] The act contradicted the ministry's edict to "promote national culture and traditions" by outlawing the broadcast of the majority of the country's traditional films, music and programming.
[src:copyright-infringement/afghanistan-and-copyright-issues] Trademarks and service marks are both registered for renewable ten-year terms through the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Afghanistan, which has adopted the 8th edition of the International Classification of Goods and Services.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] The **Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights** (**TRIPS**) is an international legal agreement between all the member nations of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] It establishes minimum standards for the regulation by national governments of different forms of intellectual property (IP) as applied to nationals of other WTO member nations.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] TRIPS was negotiated at the end of the Uruguay Round of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) between 1989 and 1990 and is administered by the WTO.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] The TRIPS agreement introduced intellectual property law into the multilateral trading system for the first time and remains the most comprehensive multilateral agreement on intellectual property to date.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] In 2001, developing countries, concerned that developed countries were insisting on an overly narrow reading of TRIPS, initiated a round of talks that resulted in the Doha Declaration.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] TRIPS also specifies enforcement procedures, remedies, and dispute resolution procedures.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] TRIPS was negotiated during the Uruguay Round of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) in 1986–1994.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Its inclusion was the culmination of a program of intense lobbying by the United States by the International Intellectual Property Alliance, supported by the European Union, Japan and other developed nations.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Unlike other agreements on intellectual property, TRIPS has a powerful enforcement mechanism.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] States can be disciplined through the WTO's dispute settlement mechanism.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] TRIPS requires member states to provide strong protection for intellectual property rights.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] The TRIPS Agreement incorporates by reference the provisions on copyright from the Berne Convention for the Protection of Literary and Artistic Works (Art 9), with the exception of moral rights.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] It also incorporated by reference the substantive provisions of the Paris Convention for the Protection of Industrial Property (Art 2.1).
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] The TRIPS Agreement specifically mentions that software and databases are protected by copyright, subject to originality requirement (Art 10).
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] The obligations under TRIPS apply equally to all member states; however, developing countries were allowed extra time to implement the applicable changes to their national laws, in two tiers of transition according to their level of development.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] The transition period for developing countries expired in 2005.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] The transition period for least developed countries to implement TRIPS was extended to 2013, and until 1 January 2016 for pharmaceutical patents, with the possibility of further extension.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] It has therefore been argued that the TRIPS standard of requiring all countries to create strict intellectual property systems will be detrimental to poorer countries' development.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] It has been argued that it is, *prima facie*, in the strategic interest of most if not all underdeveloped nations to use the flexibility available in TRIPS to legislate the weakest IP laws possible.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Banerjee and Nayak shows that TRIPS has a positive effect on R&D expenditure of Indian pharmaceutical firms.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] In addition to the baseline intellectual property standards created by the TRIPS agreement, many nations have engaged in bilateral agreements to adopt a higher standard of protection.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] These collection of standards, known as TRIPS+ or TRIPS-Plus, can take many forms.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] According to *WTO 10th Anniversary, Highlights of the first decade, Annual Report 2005* page 142, in the first ten years, 25 complaints have been lodged leading to the panel reports and appellate body reports on TRIPS listed below.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Since TRIPS came into force, it has been subject to criticism from developing countries, academics, and non-governmental organizations.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Though some of this criticism is against the WTO generally, many advocates of trade liberalisation also regard TRIPS as poor policy.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Other criticism has focused on the failure of TRIPS to accelerate investment and technology flows to low-income countries, a benefit advanced by WTO members in the lead-up to the agreement's formation.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Statements by the World Bank indicate that TRIPS has not led to a demonstrable acceleration of investment to low-income countries, though it may have done so for middle-income countries.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Daniele Archibugi and Andrea Filippetti have argued that the main motive for TRIPS was a decline in the competitiveness of the technology industry in the United States, Japan, and the European Union against emerging markets, which it largely failed to abate.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] They instead argue that the main supporters and beneficiaries of TRIPS were IP-intensive multinational corporations in these countries, and that TRIPS enabled them to outsource key operations to emerging markets.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Archibugi and Filippetti also argue that the importance of TRIPS, and intellectual property in general, in the process of generation and diffusion of knowledge and innovation has been overestimated by its supporters.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] This point has been supported by United Nations findings indicating many countries with weak protection routinely benefit from strong levels of foreign direct investment (FDI).
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Analysis of OECD countries in the 1980s and 1990s (during which the patent life of drugs was extended by six years) showed that while total number of products registered increased slightly, the mean innovation index remained unchanged.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] They argue, however, that the benefits from weakening intellectual property rights strongly depend on whether the governments can credibly commit to using it only in exceptional cases of emergencies since firms may invest less in R&D if they expect repeated episodes of compulsory licensing.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] TRIPS-plus conditions mandating standards beyond TRIPS have also been the subject of scrutiny.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] These FTA agreements contain conditions that limit the ability of governments to introduce competition for generic producers.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] In particular, the United States has been criticised for advancing protection well beyond the standards mandated by TRIPS.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] The United States Free Trade Agreements with Australia, Morocco and Bahrain have extended patentability by requiring patents be available for new uses of known products.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] The TRIPS agreement allows the grant of compulsory licenses at a nation's discretion.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] TRIPS-plus conditions in the United States' FTAs with Australia, Jordan, Singapore and Vietnam have restricted the application of compulsory licenses to emergency situations, antitrust remedies, and cases of public non-commercial use.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] The most visible conflict has been over AIDS drugs in Africa.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Despite the role that patents have played in maintaining higher drug costs for public health programs across Africa, this controversy has not led to a revision of TRIPS.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Instead, an interpretive statement, the Doha Declaration, was issued in November 2001, which indicated that TRIPS should not prevent states from dealing with public health crises and allowed for compulsory licenses.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] After Doha, PhRMA, the United States and to a lesser extent other developed nations began working to minimize the effect of the declaration.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] In 2001, at the Fourth Ministerial Conference in Doha, several World Trade Organization (WTO) members proposed changes to Articles 27 and 31 of the TRIPS Agreement, aiming to strike a balance between patent protection for pharmaceuticals and the impact of such protection on drug prices.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] This initiative led to the Doha Declaration, which reaffirmed the sovereign right of WTO members to grant compulsory licenses for pharmaceuticals.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] The Declaration also acknowledged the struggles faced by countries with limited pharmaceutical manufacturing capabilities in utilizing compulsory licensing under TRIPS, signaling perceived limitations within the original TRIPS framework.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Following two years of intense negotiations, the TRIPS Council responded by implementing the Waiver Decision in 2003, which temporarily allowed WTO members to grant compulsory licenses free from the restrictions of TRIPS Articles 31(f) and 31(h).
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] The principles of this decision were later codified into TRIPS through the Amendment Protocol of 2005, which introduced Article 31bis, effectively becoming law in 2017 post-ratification by two-thirds of WTO members.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Article 31bis allows a WTO member with insufficient or no manufacturing capacities in the pharmaceutical sector (the "Importing State") to import patented pharmaceutical products produced under a special export compulsory license granted by another WTO member (the "Exporting State").
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] It is structured as a dialogical interaction between an Importing State and an Exporting State and has specific procedural requirements.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] The Exporting State can issue an export compulsory license exempt from Article 31(f) restrictions, but the license must comply with several specific terms.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Developed WTO members can opt-out from being Importing States, but the COVID-19 pandemic revealed the potential shortfalls of this decision as several developed countries struggled with inadequate vaccine production capabilities.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] In 2003, the US Bush administration changed its position, concluding that generic treatments might in fact be a component of an effective strategy to combat HIV.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Bush created the PEPFAR program, which received $15 billion from 2003 to 2007, and was reauthorized in 2008 for $48 billion over the next five years.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Despite wavering on the issue of compulsory licensing, PEPFAR began to distribute generic drugs in 2004–05.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] In 2020, conflicts re-emerged over patents, copyrights and trade secrets related to COVID-19 vaccines, diagnostics and treatments.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] South Africa and India proposed that WTO grant a temporary waiver to enable more widespread production of the vaccines, since suppressing the virus as quickly as possible benefits the entire world.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] The waivers would be in addition to the existing, but cumbersome, flexibilities in TRIPS allowing countries to impose compulsory licenses.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Over 100 developing nations supported the waiver but it was blocked by the G7 members.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] This blocking was condemned by 400 organizations including Doctors Without Borders and 115 members of the European Parliament.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] In June 2022, after extensive involvement of the European Union, the WTO instead adopted a watered-down agreement that focuses only on vaccine patents, excludes high-income countries and China, and contains few provisions that are not covered by existing flexibilities.
[src:copyright-infringement/agreement-on-trade-related-aspects-of-intellectual-property-rights] Another controversy has been over the TRIPS Article 27 requirements for patentability "in all fields of technology", and whether or not this necessitates the granting of software and business method patents.
[src:copyright-infringement/apc-magazine] The magazine's website publishes daily technology news, mostly separate from the printed magazine.
[src:copyright-infringement/apc-magazine] The magazine was bought from Bauer Media Group in 2013 by Future.
[src:copyright-infringement/apc-magazine] Future subsequently incorporated *PC & Tech Authority* into *APC* after acquiring it (along with other computing assets) from Nextmedia in 2018.
[src:copyright-infringement/apc-magazine] In 2022, sister magazine *TechLife* (formerly *PC User*) ceased publication and merged into *APC*.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Copyright infringement disputes are usually resolved through direct negotiation, a notice and take down process, or litigation in civil court.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Egregious or large-scale commercial infringement, especially when it involves counterfeiting, or the fraudulent imitation of a product or brand, is sometimes prosecuted via the criminal justice system.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Estimates of the actual economic impact of copyright infringement vary widely and depend on other factors.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Nevertheless, copyright holders, industry representatives, and legislators have long characterized copyright infringement as piracy or theft – language which some US courts now regard as pejorative or otherwise contentious.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The terms *piracy* and *theft* are often associated with copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The original meaning of *piracy* is "robbery or illegal violence at sea", but the term has been in use for centuries as a synonym for acts of copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] *Theft*, meanwhile, emphasises the potential commercial harm of infringement to copyright holders.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] However, copyright is a type of intellectual property, an area of law distinct from that which covers robbery or theft, offences related only to tangible property.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Not all copyright infringement results in commercial loss, and the US Supreme Court ruled in 1985 that infringement does not easily equate with theft.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] This was taken further in the case *MPAA v.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Williams granted a motion to deny the MPAA the usage of words whose appearance was primarily "pejorative".
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] This list included the word "piracy", the use of which, the motion by the defence stated, serves no court purpose but to misguide and inflame the jury.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The term "piracy" has been used to refer to the unauthorized copying, distribution and selling of works in copyright.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In 1668, publisher John Hancock wrote of "some dishonest Booksellers, called Land-Pirats, who make it their practice to steal Impressions of other mens Copies" in the work *A String of Pearls: or, The Best Things Reserved till Last* by Thomas Brooks.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The practice of labelling the infringement of exclusive rights in creative works as "piracy" predates statutory copyright law.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Before the Statute of Anne in 1710, the Stationers' Company of London in 1557 received a royal charter giving the company a monopoly on publication and tasking it with enforcing the charter.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Copyright holders frequently refer to copyright infringement as theft, "although such misuse has been rejected by legislatures and courts".
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The slogan "Piracy is theft" was used beginning in the 1980s, and is still being used.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In copyright law, infringement does not refer to theft of physical objects that take away the owner's possession, but an instance where a person exercises one of the exclusive rights of the copyright holder without authorization.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Courts have distinguished between copyright infringement and theft.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] For instance, the United States Supreme Court held in *Dowling v.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] United States* (1985) that bootleg phonorecords did not constitute stolen property.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The term "freebooting" has been used to describe the unauthorized copying of online media, particularly videos, on social media websites.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The word itself had already been in use since the 16th century, referring to pirates, and meant "looting" or "plundering".
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] This new form of the word referring to copying social media – a portmanteau of "freeloading" and "bootlegging" – was suggested by YouTuber and podcaster Brady Haran in the podcast *Hello Internet*.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Haran advocated the term in an attempt to find a phrase more emotive than "copyright infringement", yet more appropriate than "theft".
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Sometimes only partial compliance with licence agreements is the cause.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] For example, in 2013, the United States Army settled a lawsuit with Texas-based company Apptricity which makes software that allows the army to track its soldiers in real time.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In 2004, the US Army paid the company a total of $4.5 million for a licence of 500 users while allegedly installing the software for more than 9000 users; the case was settled for US$50 million.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Major anti-piracy organizations, like the BSA, conduct software licensing audits regularly to ensure full compliance.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Cara Cusumano, director of the Tribeca Film Festival, stated in April 2014: "Piracy is less about people not wanting to pay and more about just wanting the immediacy – people saying, 'I want to watch Spiderman right now' and downloading it".
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The statement occurred during the third year that the festival used the Internet to present its content, while it was the first year that it featured a showcase of content producers who work exclusively online.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In a study published in the *Journal of Behavioural and Experimental Economics*, and reported on in early May 2014, researchers from the University of Portsmouth in the UK discussed findings from examining the illegal downloading behavior of 6,000 Finnish people, aged seven to 84.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The list of reasons for downloading given by the study respondents included money saving; the ability to access material not on general release, or before it was released; and assisting artists to avoid involvement with record companies and movie studios.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] According to the study, even though digital piracy inflicts additional costs on the production side of media, it also offers the main access to media goods in developing countries.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The strong tradeoffs that favour using digital piracy in developing economies dictate the current neglected law enforcement toward digital piracy.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In China as of 2013, the issue of digital infringement has not merely been legal, but social – originating from the high demand for cheap and affordable goods as well as the governmental connections of the businesses which produce such goods.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] There have been instances where a country's government bans a movie, resulting in the spread of copied videos and DVDs.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Romanian-born documentary maker Ilinca Calugareanu wrote a *New York Times* article telling the story of Irina Margareta Nistor, a narrator for state TV under Nicolae Ceauşescu's regime.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] A visitor from the West gave her bootlegged copies of American movies, which she dubbed for secret viewings through Romania.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] According to the article, she dubbed more than 3,000 movies and became the country's second-most famous voice after Ceauşescu, even though no one knew her name until many years later.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Most countries extend copyright protections to authors of works.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In countries with copyright legislation, enforcement of copyright is generally the responsibility of the copyright holder.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] However, in several jurisdictions there are also criminal penalties for copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] According to the US Chamber of Commerce's 2021 IP Index, the nations with the lowest scores for copyright protection were Vietnam, Pakistan, Egypt, Nigeria, Brunei, Algeria, Venezuela and Argentina.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Copyright infringement in civil law is any violation of the exclusive rights of the owner.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In US law, these rights include reproduction, preparation of derivative works, distribution of copies by sale or rental, and public performances or displays.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In the United States, copyright infringement is sometimes confronted via lawsuits in civil court, against alleged infringers directly or against providers of services and software that support unauthorized copying.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] For example, major motion-picture corporation MGM Studios filed suit against P2P file-sharing services Grokster and Streamcast for their contributory role in copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In 2005, the Supreme Court ruled in favor of MGM, holding that such services could be held liable for copyright infringement since they functioned and, indeed, wilfully marketed themselves as venues for acquiring copyrighted movies.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Grokster* case did not overturn the earlier *Sony v.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Universal City Studios* decision, but rather clouded the legal waters; future designers of software capable of being used for copyright infringement were warned.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In the United States, the copyright term has been extended many times over from the original term of 14 years with a single renewal allowance of 14 years, to the current term of the life of the author plus 70 years.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] If the work was produced under corporate authorship it may last 120 years after creation or 95 years after publication, whichever is sooner.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Article 50 of the Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights (TRIPs) requires that signatory countries enable courts to remedy copyright infringement with injunctions and the destruction of infringing products, and award damages.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Some jurisdictions only allow actual, provable damages, and some, like the United States, allow for large statutory damage awards intended to deter would-be infringers and allow for compensation in situations where actual damages are difficult to prove.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In some jurisdictions, copyright or the right to enforce it can be contractually assigned to a third party that did not have a role in producing the work.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Punishment of copyright infringement varies case-by-case across countries.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Convictions may include jail time or severe fines for each instance of copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In the United States, wilful copyright infringement carries a maximum fine of $150,000 per instance.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Article 61 of the Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights (TRIPs) requires that signatory countries establish criminal procedures and penalties in cases of "willful trademark counterfeiting or copyright piracy on a commercial scale".
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Copyright holders have demanded that states provide criminal sanctions for all types of copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The first criminal provision in US copyright law was added in 1897, which established a misdemeanor penalty for "unlawful performances and representations of copyrighted dramatic and musical compositions" if the violation had been "willful and for profit".
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Criminal copyright infringement requires that the infringer acted "for the purpose of commercial advantage or private financial gain" (17 U.S.C. § 506).
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] To establish criminal liability, the prosecutor must first show the basic elements of copyright infringement: ownership of a valid copyright, and the violation of one or more of the copyright holder's exclusive rights.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The government must then establish that the defendant wilfully infringed or, in other words, possessed the necessary *mens rea*.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Misdemeanor infringement has a very low threshold in terms of the number of copies and the value of the infringed works.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The ACTA trade agreement, signed in May 2011 by the United States, Japan, and the EU, requires that its parties add criminal penalties, including incarceration and fines, for copyright and trademark infringement, and obligated the parties to actively police for infringement.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Maximum penalties can be five years in prison and up to $250,000 in fines.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The NET Act also raised statutory damages by 50%.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The court's ruling explicitly drew attention to the shortcomings of current law that allowed people to facilitate mass copyright infringement while being immune to prosecution under the Copyright Act.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Proposed laws such as the Stop Online Piracy Act broaden the definition of "willful infringement", and introduce felony charges for unauthorized media streaming.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] These bills are aimed towards defeating websites that carry or contain links to infringing content, but have raised concerns about domestic abuse and internet censorship.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] To an extent, copyright law in some countries permits downloading copyright-protected content for personal, noncommercial use.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Examples include Canada and European Union (EU) member states like Poland.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The personal copying exemption in the copyright law of EU member states stems from the Information Society Directive of 2001, which is generally devised to allow EU members to enact laws permitting making copies without authorization, as long as they are for personal, noncommercial use.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Rights-holder compensation takes various forms, depending on the country, but is generally either a levy on "recording" devices and media, or a tax on the content itself.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In some countries, such as Canada, the applicability of such laws to copying onto general-purpose storage devices like computer hard drives, portable media players, and phones, for which no levies are collected, has been the subject of debate and further efforts to reform copyright law.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In some countries, the personal copying exemption explicitly requires that the content being copied be obtained legitimately (i.e. from authorized sources, not file-sharing networks).
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Although downloading or other private copying is sometimes permitted, public distribution – by uploading or otherwise offering to share copyright-protected content – remains illegal in most, if not all, countries.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] For example, in Canada, even though it was once legal to download any copyrighted file as long as it was for noncommercial use, it was still illegal to distribute the copyrighted files (e.g. by uploading them to a P2P network).
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Some countries, like Canada and Germany, have limited the penalties for non-commercial copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] For example, Germany has passed a bill to limit the fine for individuals accused of sharing movies and series to €800–900.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Title I of the US DMCA, the WIPO Copyright and Performances and Phonograms Treaties Implementation Act has provisions that prevent persons from "circumvent[ing] a technological measure that effectively controls access to a work".
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Apple Inc.*, it is legal to point users to DRM-stripping software and inform them how to use it because of lack of evidence that DRM stripping leads to copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Whether Internet intermediaries are liable for copyright infringement by their users is a subject of debate and court cases in a number of countries.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Internet intermediaries were formerly understood to be internet service providers (ISPs).
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] However, questions of liability have also emerged in relation to other Internet infrastructure intermediaries, including Internet backbone providers, cable companies and mobile communications providers.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Early court cases focused on the liability of Internet service providers (ISPs) for hosting, transmitting or publishing user-supplied content that could be actioned under civil or criminal law, such as libel or pornography.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The debate has shifted away from questions about liability for specific content, including that which may infringe copyright, towards whether online intermediaries should be generally responsible for content accessible through their services or infrastructure.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The US Digital Millennium Copyright Act (October 1998) and the European E-Commerce Directive (June 2000) provide online intermediaries with limited statutory immunity from liability for copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Online intermediaries hosting content that infringes copyright are not liable, so long as they do not know about it and take action once the infringing content is brought to their attention.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In US law this is characterized as "safe harbor" provisions.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Under European law, the governing principles for Internet Service Providers are "mere conduit", meaning that they are neutral 'pipes' with no knowledge of what they are carrying; and 'no obligation to monitor' meaning that they cannot be given a general mandate by governments to monitor content.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] These two principles are a barrier for certain forms of online copyright enforcement and they were the reason behind an attempt to amend the European Telecoms Package in 2009 to support new measures against copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Peer-to-peer file sharing intermediaries have been denied access to safe harbor provisions in relation to copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Legal action against such intermediaries, such as Napster, is generally brought in relation to principles of secondary liability for copyright infringement, such as contributory liability and vicarious liability.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] These types of intermediaries do not host or transmit infringing content themselves, but may be regarded in some courts as encouraging, enabling or facilitating infringement by users.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] These intermediaries may include the authors, publishers, and marketers of peer-to-peer networking software, and the websites that allow users to download such software.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In the case of the BitTorrent protocol, intermediaries may include the torrent tracker and any websites or search engines which facilitate access to torrent files.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Torrent files do not contain copyrighted content, but they may refer to files that do, and they may point to trackers which coordinate the sharing of those files.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Some torrent indexing and search sites, such as The Pirate Bay, now encourage the use of magnet links, instead of direct links to torrent files, creating another layer of indirection; using such links, torrent files are obtained from other peers, rather than from a particular website.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Nevertheless, whether and to what degree any of these types of intermediaries have secondary liability is the subject of ongoing litigation.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The decentralized structure of peer-to-peer networks, in particular, does not sit easily with existing laws on online intermediaries' liability.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The BitTorrent protocol established an entirely decentralized network architecture in order to distribute large files effectively.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Recent developments in peer-to-peer technology towards more complex network configurations are said to have been driven by a desire to avoid liability as intermediaries under existing laws.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Copyright law does not grant authors and publishers absolute control over the use of their work.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Only certain types of works and kinds of uses are protected; only unauthorized uses of protected works can be said to be infringing.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The laws implementing these limitations and exceptions for uses that would otherwise be infringing broadly fall into the categories of either fair use or fair dealing.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In common law systems, these fair practice statutes typically enshrine principles underlying many earlier judicial precedents, and are considered essential to freedom of speech.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Another example is the practice of compulsory licensing, which is where the law forbids copyright owners from denying a licence for certain uses of certain kinds of works, such as compilations and live performances of music.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Compulsory licensing laws generally say that for certain uses of certain works, no infringement occurs as long as a royalty, at a rate determined by law rather than private negotiation, is paid to the copyright owner or representative copyright collective.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Some fair dealing laws, such as Canada's, include similar royalty requirements.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The first prong was decided in favor of the news generators; in June 2014 the second prong was decided by the Court of Justice of the European Union (CJEU), which ruled that the temporary web cache of consumers of the aggregator did not infringe the copyright of the news generators.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In order to qualify for protection, a work must be an expression with a degree of originality, and it must be in a fixed medium, such as written down on paper or recorded digitally.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] That is, a copy of someone else's original idea is not infringing unless it copies that person's unique, tangible expression of the idea.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Some of these limitations, especially regarding what qualifies as original, are embodied only in case law (judicial precedent), rather than in statutes.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In the United States, for example, copyright case law contains a substantial similarity requirement to determine whether the work was copied.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Likewise, courts may require computer software to pass an Abstraction-Filtration-Comparison test (AFC Test) to determine if it is too abstract to qualify for protection, or too dissimilar to an original work to be considered infringing.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Software-related case law has also clarified that the amount of R&D, effort and expense put into a work's creation does not affect copyright protection.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Evaluation of alleged copyright infringement in a court of law may be substantial; the time and costs required to apply these tests vary based on the size and complexity of the copyrighted material.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Furthermore, there is no standard or universally accepted test; some courts have rejected the AFC Test, for example, in favor of narrower criteria.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Corporations and legislatures take different types of preventive measures to deter copyright infringement, with much of the focus since the early 1990s being on preventing or reducing digital methods of infringement.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Legislatures have reduced infringement by narrowing the scope of what is considered infringing.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Aside from upholding international copyright treaty obligations to provide general limitations and exceptions, nations have enacted compulsory licensing laws applying specifically to digital works and uses.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] For example, in the US, the DMCA, an implementation of the 1996 WIPO Copyright Treaty, considers digital transmissions of audio recordings to be licensed as long as a designated copyright collective's royalty and reporting requirements are met.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The DMCA also provides safe harbor for digital service providers whose users are suspected of copyright infringement, thus reducing the likelihood that the providers themselves will be considered directly infringing.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] This has the effect of reducing infringement – and the burden on courts – by simply permitting certain types of uses under terms that the copyright owner considers reasonable.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Examples include free software licences, like the GNU General Public License (GPL), and the Creative Commons licences, which are predominantly applied to visual and literary works.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] To maximize revenue, pre-COVID-19 film distribution typically began with cinemas (theatrical window), on average approximately 16+1⁄2 weeks, before the release to Blu-ray and DVD (entering its video window).
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] During the theatrical window, digital versions of films are often transported in data storage devices by couriers rather than by data transmission.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The data can be encrypted, with the key being made to work only at specific times in order to prevent leakage between screens.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Coded anti-piracy marks can be added to films to identify the source of illegal copies and shut them down.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] In 2006, a notable example of using Coded Anti-Piracy marks resulted in a man being arrested for uploading a screener's copy of the movie *Flushed Away*.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] Some photocopiers use Machine Identification Code dots for similar purposes.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p01] The EURion constellation on banknotes is used to prevent copying to make counterfeit currency.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] Organisations disagree on the scope and magnitude of copyright infringement's free rider economic effects and public support for the copyright regime.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] 30,000 users, including minors between 14 and 17 years, were surveyed between September and October 2014.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] According to the European Digital Rights association, the study may have been censored: specifically, as of 2018, the European Commission has not published the results, except in the part where the film industry was found to be adversely affected by illegal content consumption.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] Access to the study was requested and obtained by Member of the European Parliament Felix Reda.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] The US GAO's 2010 findings regarding the great difficulty of accurately gauging the economic impact of copyright infringement were reinforced within the same report by the body's research into three commonly cited estimates that had previously been provided to US agencies.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] In 2008, the Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA) reported that its six major member companies lost US$6.1 billion to piracy.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] A 2009 *Los Angeles Daily News* article then cited a loss figure of "roughly $20 billion a year" for Hollywood studios.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] According to a 2013 article in *The Wall Street Journal*, industry estimates in the United States range between $6.1B to $18.5B per year.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] In an early May 2014 article in *The Guardian*, an annual loss figure of US$20.5 billion was cited for the movie industry.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] The article's basis is the results of a University of Portsmouth study that only involved Finnish participants, aged between seven and 84.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] The researchers, who worked with 6,000 participants, stated: "Movie pirates are also more likely to cut down their piracy if they feel they are harming the industry compared with people who illegally download music".
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] Psion Software claimed in 1983 that software piracy cost it £2.9 million a year, 30% of its revenue.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] Will Wright said that *Raid on Bungeling Bay* sold 20,000 copies for the Commodore 64 in the US, but 800,000 cartridges for the Nintendo Famicom with a comparable installed base in Japan, "because it's a cartridge system [so] there's virtually no piracy".
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] According to a 2007 BSA and International Data Corporation (IDC) study, the five countries with the highest rates of software piracy were: 1.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] According to the study's results, the five countries with the lowest piracy rates were: 1. the US (20%); 2.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] According to the 2011 study, Zimbabwe was the nation with the highest piracy rate, at 92%, while the lowest piracy rate was present in the US, at 19%.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] In 2007, the Institute for Policy Innovation (IPI) reported that music piracy took $12.5 billion from the US economy.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] According to the study, musicians and those involved in the recording industry are not the only ones who experience losses attributed to music piracy.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] Retailers have lost over a billion dollars, while piracy has resulted in 46,000 fewer production-level jobs and almost 25,000 retail jobs.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] The US government was also reported to suffer from music piracy, losing $422 million in tax revenue.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] A 2007 study in the *Journal of Political Economy* found that the effect of music downloads on legal music sales was "statistically indistinguishable from zero".
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] A report from 2013, released by the European Commission Joint Research Centre suggests that illegal music downloads have almost no effect on the number of legal music downloads.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] The study analysed the behaviour of 16,000 European music consumers and found that although music piracy negatively affects offline music sales, illegal music downloads had a positive effect on legal music purchases.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] Without illegal downloading, legal purchases were about two per cent lower.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] The study has received criticism, particularly from the International Federation of the Phonographic Industry, which believes the study is flawed and misleading.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] One argument against the research is that many music consumers only download music illegally.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] The IFPI also points out that music piracy affects not only online music sales but also multiple facets of the music industry, which is not addressed in the study.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] In a March 2019 article, *The New York Times* reported that the Qatar-based beIN Media Group suffered "billions of dollars" of losses, following the unilateral cancellation of an exclusive contract it shared with the Asian Football Confederation (AFC) for the past 10 years.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] In January 2020, the European Commission released a report on protection and enforcement of intellectual property rights in third countries.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] The report named as many as 13 countries, including Argentina, Brazil, China, Ecuador, India, Indonesia, and Saudi Arabia, the last being included for the first time.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] The report said piracy is "causing considerable harm to EU businesses" and high economic losses have occurred in Argentina, China, Ecuador and India.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] It also informed that Saudi Arabia has not "taken sufficient steps to stop the infringement" caused via BeoutQ, like other countries have, to minimize the extent of financial and economic loss.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] In addition to suffering losses to income, copyright holders can end up spending up to 10 thousand dollars proving in court when dealing with piracy which can divert resources away from creating new creative works.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] This includes communication, planning, necessary court filings, meetings with opposing counsel or judges dealing with lawsuits that can typically last for months to years and costing from $5000 to $350,000.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] Artists may need to reclaim their right to their own copyright and the process can last for up to months.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] And if they were for whatever reason not successful, they may need to appeal or create a new work.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] Some claims made by industry representatives have been criticized as overestimating the monetary loss caused by copyright infringement.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] In one example, the RIAA claimed damages against LimeWire totalling $75 trillion – more than the global GDP – with the judge overseeing the case ruling that such claims were "absurd".
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] The $75 trillion figure had been obtained by counting each song downloaded as an infringement of copyright.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] After the conclusion of the case, LimeWire agreed to pay $105 million to RIAA.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] In another decision, US District Court Judge James P.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] Jones found that the "RIAA's request problematically assumes that every illegal download resulted in a lost sale", indicating profit/loss estimates were likely extremely off.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] Critics of industry estimates argue that those who use peer-to-peer sharing services, or practice "piracy" are actually more likely to pay for music.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] Professor Aram Sinnreich, in his book *The Piracy Crusade*, states that the connection between declining music sales and the creation of peer-to-peer file sharing sites such as Napster is tenuous, based on correlation rather than causation.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] He argues that the industry at the time was undergoing artificial expansion, what he describes as a "'perfect bubble'—a confluence of economic, political, and technological forces that drove the aggregate value of music sales to unprecedented heights at the end of the twentieth century".
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] Sinnreich cites multiple causes for the economic bubble, including the CD format replacement cycle; the shift from music speciality stores to wholesale suppliers of music and 'minimum advertised pricing'; and the economic expansion of 1991–2001.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] He believes that with the introduction of new digital technologies, the bubble burst, and the industry suffered as a result.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] The 2011 Business Software Alliance Piracy Study Standard estimated the total commercial value of illegally copied software to be at $59 billion in 2010, with emerging markets accounting for $31.9 billion, over half of the total.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] Furthermore, mature markets for the first time received fewer PC shipments than emerging economies in 2010.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] In addition, software infringement rates were 68 per cent compared to 24 per cent in mature markets; thus, emerging markets possessed the majority of the global increase in the commercial value of counterfeit software.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] China continued to have the highest commercial value of such software at $8.9 billion among developing countries and second in the world behind the US at $9.7 billion in 2011.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] In 2011, the Business Software Alliance announced that 83 per cent of software deployed on PCs in Africa had been pirated (excluding South Africa).
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] Some countries distinguish corporate piracy from private use, which is tolerated as a welfare service.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] This is the leading reason developing countries refuse to accept or respect copyright laws.
[src:copyright-infringement/copyright-infringement-p02] Traian Băsescu, the president of Romania from 2004 to 2014, stated that "piracy helped the young generation discover computers.
